        Selling the Family Home to Fund Aged Care in Queensland
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        When a parent enters residential aged care, the family home often needs to be sold. The timing, the means test, and the financial structure all matter. Here is what Queensland families need to know.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The decision to sell a family home to fund residential aged care is one of the most emotionally and financially significant transactions many families will ever manage. It typically arrives with little warning: a parent's health declines, a care facility must be chosen and a deposit paid, and within weeks a family finds itself needing to decide what to do with a property that may have been the centre of family life for decades. Getting the decision right requires understanding both the aged care system and the property market, and making sure those two sets of advice are working together.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How residential aged care costs are structured</h2>
      <p>Residential aged care facilities in Australia charge residents under two main cost categories: accommodation costs and care costs. The accommodation cost can be paid in one of two ways. A Refundable Accommodation Deposit (RAD) is a lump sum payment to the facility that is refunded in full when the resident leaves or passes away. A Daily Accommodation Payment (DAP) is the equivalent of the RAD expressed as a daily rental charge. Most families choose a combination of the two, and the facility must offer this option. The RAD can be substantial, typically ranging from several hundred thousand dollars to over a million dollars for higher-quality facilities in metropolitan areas.</p>

      <p>Care costs are separate and include a basic daily fee (set by the government as a percentage of the single age pension) and a means-tested care fee, which depends on the resident's income and assets. The means-tested care fee is where the sale of the family home has the most significant ongoing financial impact, because once the home becomes an assessable asset, it increases the resident's assessed wealth and therefore the means-tested care fee they are charged.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The two-year exemption and what happens after it</h2>
      <p>When a person enters residential aged care, the family home is initially exempt from the means test, provided a protected person continues to live there. A protected person is defined as a spouse or de facto partner, a dependent child, or a carer who has lived in the home continuously for at least two years immediately before the resident entered care. If no protected person is living in the property, the two-year exemption still applies, but the clock starts running from the date the resident entered care.</p>

      <p>After the two-year exemption period ends, the home is included as an assessable asset in the means test, subject to a capped value currently set by Services Australia. This has two effects: it increases the resident's assessed assets, which may increase their means-tested care fee, and it affects any pension entitlements if the resident was receiving the age pension. For many families, the two-year exemption window is an important consideration in deciding when to sell. Selling before or after the two-year mark can have meaningful financial implications, and an aged care financial adviser can model the specific numbers for your situation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Selling versus renting the home to fund care costs</h2>
      <p>Some families consider renting the family home rather than selling it, using rental income to fund care costs, particularly the DAP, while retaining the asset for future beneficiaries. This can work financially in some circumstances, but it is not straightforward. Rental income is assessable in the means test and will affect means-tested care fees and pension calculations. The property also needs to be maintained, managed, and eventually dealt with on the resident's death or when care arrangements change. Whether retaining the home makes financial sense depends on the specific numbers: the rental yield, the cost of the RAD versus the DAP, the resident's total asset position, and the family's capacity to manage a rental property alongside the demands of supporting an elderly parent. This is genuinely a question for an aged care financial adviser, not a real estate agent.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why financial advice must come before the sale decision</h2>
      <p>The interaction between the aged care means test, the age pension, capital gains tax, and the structure of care fees is genuinely complex. Decisions made without proper advice can be difficult or impossible to unwind. An aged care financial adviser accredited under the Financial Planning Association's aged care specialist pathway understands this intersection and can model the financial outcomes of different scenarios: selling before the two-year exemption, selling after it, using all proceeds for the RAD, or using a combination of RAD and DAP. This modelling should be done before the property is listed, not after an offer has been accepted.</p>

      <p>A solicitor experienced in aged care and estate planning should also be part of the professional team. If the property owner has lost capacity to manage their affairs, questions about power of attorney or guardianship may also need to be resolved before the sale can proceed (see our separate article on selling under power of attorney).</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What families need from their real estate agent</h2>
      <p>Families selling a family home to fund aged care need an agent who understands the constraints they are working under and can manage the sale accordingly. In some cases, the two-year exemption window creates genuine time pressure: the family needs a good result and needs it within a defined period. In other cases, there is flexibility, and a better-prepared campaign will produce a meaningfully better outcome than rushing to market.</p>

      <p>Presentation matters, even under time pressure. A long-held family home that has not been updated recently will not present at its best without some focused preparation. This does not need to be extensive or expensive. In Brisbane's inner east, the properties that achieve the strongest results from families in these circumstances are the ones where someone has taken the time to declutter, address the obvious maintenance items, and present the home cleanly. Buyers are sensitive to a property that appears to have been listed under duress, and a hurried, under-prepared campaign signals exactly that.</p>

      <p>The emotional dimension of these sales also matters. The property may have been owned for 30 or 40 years. Adult children may have different views about whether and when to sell. The parent entering care may still have strong feelings about the home and what happens to it. An experienced agent in these situations knows how to manage the campaign professionally while being sensitive to the fact that for the family, this is not just a transaction.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Getting the timing right</h2>
      <p>The right time to sell depends on the interaction between the means test clock, the property market, and the family's preparation. In Brisbane's inner east, well-presented family homes in good school catchments continue to attract genuine buyer demand across most market conditions. If the financial modelling says you need to sell within the two-year exemption window, that is the constraint you work within, and a properly run campaign in that timeframe should deliver a sound result. If there is flexibility, take the time to prepare the property and choose the campaign timing that local market conditions support. Either way, the decision about when to sell should follow the financial advice, not precede it.</p>

